# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alliance-of-european-national-movements
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] The **2019 European Parliament election** was held in the European Union (EU) between 23 and 26 May 2019.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] It was the ninth parliamentary election since the first direct elections in 1979.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] A total of 751 Members of the European Parliament (MEPs) were elected to represent more than 512 million people from 28 member states.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] In February 2018, the European Parliament had voted to decrease the number of MEPs from 751 to 705 if the United Kingdom were to withdraw from the European Union on 29 March 2019.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] However, the United Kingdom participated alongside other EU member states after an extension of Article 50 to 31 October 2019; therefore, the allocation of seats between the member states and the total number of seats remained as it had been in 2014.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] On 26 May 2019, the centre-left and centre-right parties suffered significant losses, while pro-EU centrist, liberal and environmentalist parties and anti-EU right-wing populist parties made substantial gains.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] The European People's Party led by Manfred Weber won the most seats in the European Parliament, making Weber the leading candidate to become the next President of the European Commission.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] Despite this, the European Council decided after the election to nominate Ursula von der Leyen as new Commission President.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] On 7 June 2018, the Council agreed at ambassador level to change the EU electoral law and to reform old laws from the 1976 Electoral Act.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] The purpose of the reform is to increase participation in elections, raise understanding of their European character and prevent irregular voting while at the same time respecting the constitutional and electoral traditions of the member states.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] The reform forbids double voting and voting in third countries, thus improving the visibility of European political parties.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] To avoid double voting, contact authorities are established to exchange data on voters, a process that has to start at least six weeks before the elections.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] The European Parliament gave its consent on 4 July 2018 and the Act was adopted by the Council on 13 July 2018.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] However, not all member states ratified the Act prior to the 2019 elections and therefore this election took place in line with the previous rules.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] This process was first used in 2014 and was opposed by some in the European Council.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] The future of the process is uncertain, but the European Parliament has attempted to codify the process and the parties are almost certain to select the candidates again.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] In May 2018, a Eurobarometer poll suggested that 49% of the 27,601 individuals from all 28 EU countries surveyed think that the *Spitzenkandidat* process will help them vote in the next European elections while 70% also think that the process requires a real debate on European issues.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] Incumbent Jean-Claude Juncker stated he would not seek a second term as President of the European Commission.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] At their 2018 Congress in Helsinki, the EPP elected Manfred Weber as their *Spitzenkandidat* for President of the European Commission.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] Previous candidate Martin Schulz left the European Parliament in 2017 to head the Social Democratic Party of Germany, but he stepped down from the latter position in 2018.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] Šefčovič announced his withdrawal in November and supported Frans Timmermans as the Common Candidate.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] The party convened an extraordinary Congress in Lisbon to ratify the election of the candidate and to vote upon the manifesto.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] Jan Zahradil, an MEP for the Czech Civic Democratic Party, is the *Spitzenkandidat* of the European Conservatives and Reformists.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] As in 2014, the Greens adopted the principle of having two leading candidates for the European Elections 2019.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] Unlike in 2014, where the candidates were chosen through an open online primary elections, the two leading candidates were elected by the Council of the Party in Berlin in November 2018.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] At their 2018 Congress in Berlin, the party elected Ska Keller and Bas Eickhout as their *Spitzenkandidaten* for the President of the European Commission.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] Oriol Junqueras, a Catalan historian, academic and former Vice President of Catalonia who, at the time of the election, was imprisoned because of his involvement in the 2017 Catalan independence referendum, was the *Spitzenkandidat* of the European Free Alliance.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] The designated candidates are Violeta Tomič from Slovenia and Belgian trade-unionist Nico Cué.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] The Europe of Freedom and Direct Democracy was widely expected to disband after the election.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] One reason was that its biggest share of MEPs came from the United Kingdom, which was long expected to leave the EU before the election.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] The second was that the second-biggest partner, Italy's Five Star Movement (M5S), felt uneasy about this alliance anyway, having unsuccessfully tried to join the Greens/EFA or ALDE group instead.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] In February 2019, M5S alongside partners from Croatia, Finland, Greece and Poland presented a new alliance of anti-establishment parties that claim to be neither left nor right.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] In the 5-month period preceding the 2019 European Parliament elections, the blog byoblu.com, which collaborated with the Five Star Movement (M5S), published deceptive information on Twitter, spreading disinformation during the 2019 European elections.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] The blog byoblu.com is owned by Claudio Messora, who was the head of communications for the 5 Star Movement and a close associate and friend of Beppe Grillo.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] The Movement is an alliance of populist parties set up by Steve Bannon in 2018 with the purpose of contesting the European elections.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] Participating parties included, at least temporarily, Lega Nord, People's Party of Belgium and Brothers of Italy and possibly French National Rally.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] Originally envisioned as an attempt to unite the populist parties in Europe, The Movement has so far been snubbed by the Alternative for Germany, the Freedom Party of Austria and the UK Independence Party.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] In March 2019, reporters assessed Bannon's project as a failure.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] Shortly ahead of the election, Marine Le Pen of the French National Rally distanced herself from Bannon, clarifying that he played no role in her party's campaign.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] In April 2019, Matteo Salvini of Italy's Lega launched the European Alliance of Peoples and Nations as a new coalition of populist, hard Eurosceptic and anti-immigration parties.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] It has been predicted to become the fourth largest group in parliament with an estimate of more than 80 MEPs.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] 2019 saw the debut of new parties such as Wiosna of Poland, Czech Pirate Party of Czech Republic, USR-PLUS of Romania, Human Shield and Most of Croatia, ĽSNS and Progressive Slovakia of Slovakia.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] Some of the new parties have already joined European parties, e.g.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] The new Brexit Party won 29 seats in the United Kingdom.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] As such, it won the most seats by any national political party in the parliament; the German CDU/CSU also won 29 seats but as an alliance.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] The biggest new party after UK exit is La République En Marche!
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] (LREM) of French President Emmanuel Macron that was formed in 2016 and won the French presidential and parliamentary elections of the following year.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] Initially, it balked at joining any of the existing party families, instead trying to form a new parliamentary group of pro-European centrists who support Macron's plans to reform the European institutions, drawing away members from ALDE, EPP, and S&D.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] Possible partners for such a project were expected to include Spanish Ciudadanos, Progressive Slovakia, and the Hungarian Momentum Movement.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] However, the hypothetical group was considered to have difficulties to find MEPs from at least seven member states as is required to form a new group.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] In November 2018, LREM decided to cooperate with the liberal ALDE Group instead.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] Nevertheless, Macron stressed that this was merely a loose alliance and his party is not a member of ALDE Party.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] He bluntly criticised ALDE for accepting donations from the Bayer-Monsanto chemical group while LREM's campaign chief threatened to recall the alliance.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] In April and May 2019, LREM continued its efforts to build a broader group, including ALDE, but also centrist and centre-left parties outside of ALDE.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] The European Spring initiated from the Democracy in Europe Movement 2025 ran as a pan-European party alliance with one unified vision for Europe, the European Green New Deal.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] The most prominent figure is the former Greek minister Yanis Varoufakis, who ran as a candidate in the constituency of Germany, but failed to secure a seat.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] Despite garnering approximately one and a half million votes, no representatives who ran DiEM25 were elected, due to the votes being dispersed throughout different EU countries.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] As a new pan-European party, Volt Europa was founded in different European countries two years before the elections and successfully campaigned in eight EU countries for the elections with one transnational programme.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] Despite missing its own goal to create a parliamentary group on its own, approximately half a million votes in total were sufficient to send one of the founders, Damian Boeselager, into the European Parliament via a German Volt list.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] Since June 2019, Volt is part of the group of the Greens/EFA.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] In June 2018, the European Council decided to reapportion 27 of the 73 seats which would become vacant in the event of the United Kingdom leaving the EU.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] As the United Kingdom was still a member of the EU at the time of the election, the elections were held with the same allocation of seats as in 2014.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] When the United Kingdom left the EU, 27 of the seats were reallocated to other EU member states as shown below, resulting in a total of 705 MEPs.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] The table below shows the changes in group composition after the United Kingdom left the EU.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] Renew Europe replaced the Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe group (ALDE) from the 2014−2019 Parliament.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] 198,255 votes for PS–SPOLU (Slovakia), which comprised parties which joined the RE and EPP groups, have been counted for the RE group.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] 1,252,139 votes for Ahora Repúblicas (Spain), which comprised parties which joined the G/EFA and GUE/NGL groups (plus one non-inscrit), have been counted for the G/EFA group.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] Identity and Democracy largely replaced the Europe of Nations and Freedom (ENF) group from the 2014−2019 Parliament.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] 2,258,857 votes for Unidas Podemos Cambiar Europa (Spain), which comprised parties which joined the GUE/NGL and G/EFA groups, have been counted for the GUE/NGL group.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] Geert Wilders, leader of the PVV, announced that the party would join the ID group.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] There were no pan-European polls for the European elections.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] However, several organisations calculated the theoretical seat distribution in the European Parliament based on national polls in all member states.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] The table below displays these different projections.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] Since the United Kingdom notified its intention to leave the European Union in March 2017, the United Kingdom was expected not to participate in the European elections and was therefore excluded from projections.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] On 10 April 2019, the European Council extended the Brexit deadline to 31 October 2019, and the UK did participate in the European elections.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] The UK was included in most projections after that date.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] The following table shows projections with vote share instead of seats.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] The heads of governments, gathered in a European Council on 1–3 July 2019, could not agree on a consensus President of the Commission.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] The two *Spitzenkandidaten* were discussed, but neither Manfred Weber (EPP), nor Frans Timmermans (PES), who had the backing of many leaders but not of those from the Visegrád Group, had a majority.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] In the final hours of the vote, the name of Ursula von der Leyen was suggested and agreed to by all governments, with Germany's abstention.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] The European Parliament elected Ursula von der Leyen as President of the European Commission on 16 July, with 383 votes in favour (374 votes needed).
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] The European Commission was approved by the European Parliament on 27 November 2019, receiving 461 votes, with 157 against and 89 abstentions.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2019-european-parliament-election] EPP, S&D, Renew Europe and half of the ECR voted in favour.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] Early general elections were held in Italy on 25 September 2022.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] After the fall of the Draghi government, which led to a parliamentary impasse, President Sergio Mattarella dissolved Parliament on 21 July, and called for new elections.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] Regional elections in Sicily were held on the same day.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] The results of the general election showed the centre-right coalition led by Giorgia Meloni's Brothers of Italy, a national-conservative party, winning an absolute majority of seats in the Italian Parliament.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] Meloni was appointed Prime Minister of Italy on 22 October, becoming the first woman to hold the office.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] In a record-low voter turnout, Meloni's party became the largest in Parliament with 26% of the vote; as per the pre-election agreement among the centre-right coalition parties, she became the prime ministerial candidate supported by the winning coalition.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] The League and Forza Italia suffered losses, polling 8% each, and Us Moderates polled below 1%.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] The centre-left coalition slightly improved its 2018 results in terms of vote share and seats in percentage with the Democratic Party polling 19% and the Greens and Left Alliance passing the 3% threshold; More Europe and Civic Commitment failed to reach the election threshold.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] The Five Star Movement defied single-digit polls before the campaign and reached 15%.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] The Action – Italia Viva alliance polled 7%.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] Among the others to be represented in Parliament were two regionalist parties: South calls North and the South Tyrolean People's Party.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] Due to the *Rosatellum* and its mixed electoral system using parallel voting, the centre-right coalition was able to win an absolute majority of seats, despite receiving 44% of the votes, by winning 83% of the single-member districts under the first-past-the-post of the system.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] As a result of the 2020 Italian constitutional referendum, the size of Parliament was reduced to 400 members of the Chamber of Deputies and 200 members of the Senate of the Republic to be elected, down from 630 and 315, respectively.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] In addition, the minimum voting age for the Senate was the same as for the Chamber (18 years old and no longer 25), which marked the first time the two houses had identical electorates.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] Observers commented that the results shifted the geopolitics of the European Union, following right wing populist and far-right gains in France, Spain, and Sweden.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] It was also noted that the election outcome would mark Italy's first far-right-led government and the country's most right-wing government since 1945.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] The newly elected legislature was seated on 13 October, and proceeded to elect Ignazio La Russa, a known admirer of Benito Mussolini, and Lorenzo Fontana, a strong opponent of LGBT rights, as President of the Senate and of the Chamber of Deputies, respectively.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] The Meloni Cabinet was sworn in on 22 October, and received parliamentary approval through two votes of confidence (one in each House of Parliament) a few days thereafter.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] In the 2018 Italian general election, held on 4 March, no political group or party won an outright majority, resulting in a hung parliament.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] The centre-right coalition, in which Matteo Salvini's League emerged as the main political force, won a plurality of seats in the Chamber of Deputies and in the Senate, while the anti-establishment Five Star Movement (M5S) led by Luigi Di Maio became the party with the largest number of votes.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] The centre-left coalition, led by Matteo Renzi of the governing Democratic Party (PD), came third.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] Due to the PD and centre-left's poor results, Renzi resigned on 12 March, his place being taken *ad interim* by Maurizio Martina.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] The League continued the Italian nationalist turn it took into the 2018 general election.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] In October 2018, the League was founded as a sister party to promote Salvini's candidature as Prime Minister of Italy.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] Political commentators have since described it as a parallel party of the League, with the aim of politically replacing the latter, which had been burdened by a statutory debt of €49 million.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] The League's statute presented it as a nationalist and souverainist party.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] On 22 January 2020, four days before the regional elections, Di Maio resigned as the M5S leader, and was replaced *ad interim* by Vito Crimi.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] As a result of the hung parliament, protracted negotiations were required before a new government could be formed.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] The talks between the M5S and League resulted in the proposal of the self-declared *government of change* under the leadership of Giuseppe Conte, a university law professor close to the M5S.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] After some bickering with President Sergio Mattarella, Conte's cabinet, which was dubbed by the media the "first all-populist government" in Western Europe, was sworn in on 1 June.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] The 2019 European Parliament election was a win for the League, which obtained 34 percent of the vote and 20 seats, more than any other party in the country.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] In August 2019, Deputy Prime Minister Matteo Salvini announced a motion of no confidence against Conte after growing tensions within the majority.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] Many political analysts believe the no confidence motion was an attempt to force early elections to improve the League's standing in the Italian Parliament, ensuring Salvini could become the next Prime Minister.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] On 20 August, following the parliamentary debate in which he accused Salvini of being a political opportunist who "had triggered the political crisis only to serve his personal interest", Prime Minister Conte resigned his post to President Mattarella.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] Meanwhile, the M5S started a decline in both opinion polls, deputies and senators, and election results, starting with the 2019 European Parliament election.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] After the meagre results, Di Maio won a vote of confidence in his leadership and pledged to reform the party.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] In the general election held in March 2018, the M5S had won 227 deputies and 112 senators; by February 2022, the party had declined to 157 deputies and 62 senators, though it remained the biggest party in the parliament.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] On 21 August President Mattarella started the consultations with all the parliamentary groups.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] On the same day, the national direction of the PD officially opened to a cabinet with the M5S, based on pro-Europeanism, a green economy, sustainable development, the fight against economic inequality, and a new immigration policy.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] As the talks resulted in an unclear outcome, President Mattarella announced a second round of consultation for 27 or 28 August.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] In the days that preceded the second round, a confrontation between the PD and the M5S started, while the left-wing parliamentary group LeU announced its support for a potential M5S–PD cabinet.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] On 28 August, the PD's newly elected secretary Nicola Zingaretti announced at the Quirinal Palace his favourable position on forming a new government with the M5S, with Conte at its head.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] On the same day, Mattarella summoned Conte to the Quirinal Palace for 29 August to give him the task of forming a new cabinet.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] On 3 September, members of the M5S voted on the Rousseau platform in favour of an agreement with the PD under the premiership of Conte, with more than 79% of votes out of nearly 80,000 voters.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] On 4 September, Conte announced the ministers of his new cabinet, which was sworn in at the Quirinal Palace on the following day.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] On 18 September, Renzi left the PD to found the liberal party Italia Viva (IV); he then joined the government with IV to keep the League and Salvini out of power.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] In October 2019 Parliament approved the Fraccaro Reform, named after Riccardo Fraccaro, the M5S deputy who was the bill's first signatory.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] The fourth and final vote in the Chamber of Deputies came on 8 October 2019, with 553 votes in favour and 14 against.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] In the final vote, the bill was supported by both the majority and the opposition; only the liberal party More Europe (+E) and other small groups voted against.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] The reform provided a cut in the number of MPs, which would shrink from 630 to 400 deputies and from 315 to 200 senators.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] On 20–21 September 2020, Italians largely approved the reform with nearly 70% of votes through a constitutional referendum.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] In January 2020, Italy became one of the countries worst affected by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] Conte's government was the first in the Western world to implement a national lockdown to stop the spread of the disease.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] Despite being widely approved by public opinion, the lockdown was also described as the largest suppression of constitutional rights in the history of the Italian Republic.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] In January 2021, Renzi's party Italia Viva withdrew its support for Conte's government, starting a government crisis.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] Although Conte was able to win confidence votes in Parliament in the subsequent days, he chose to resign due to failing to reach an absolute majority in the Senate.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] After negotiations to form a third Conte cabinet failed, Mario Draghi, the former president of the European Central Bank, became Prime Minister on 13 February at the head of a national unity government composed of independent technocrats and politicians from the League, M5S, PD, FI, IV, and LeU.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] Giorgia Meloni's Brothers of Italy (FdI) was the sole main party at the opposition.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] In March 2021, the PD's secretary Zingaretti resigned after growing tensions within the PD, with the party's minority accusing him for the management of the government crisis.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] Many prominent members of the party asked to former Prime Minister Enrico Letta to become the new leader; on 14 March, he was elected as the new secretary by the PD's national assembly.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] In August 2021, Conte was elected president of the M5S.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] In February 2022, a Naples' court ruled in favour of three M5S activists, suspending Conte's presidency.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] On 19 February, Conte appealed to the court's decision, on the grounds that he was not aware of the 2018 party statute, which provided for the exclusion from voting of those who had joined the M5S for less than six months, and the voting procedure was valid.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] In the Italian presidential election held in late January 2022, President Mattarella was re-elected, despite having ruled out a second term, after the governing parties asked him to do so when no other candidate was viable.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] Despite having voted in favour of military aid, the Five Star Movement, the League and Forza Italia later became increasingly critical of support to Ukraine, causing tensions in the majority.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] During summer 2022, rumours arose that M5S might withdraw its support of the national unity government, including allegations that Draghi privately criticised Conte and asked M5S founder Beppe Grillo to replace him.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] This came amid tension between the M5S and the Draghi government on economic and environmental issues, and the Russo-Ukrainian War, which also caused a split within the M5S.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] In June 2022, Di Maio formed Together for the Future (IpF), which continued to support the Draghi government.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] On 12 July, Draghi stated he would resign if the M5S withdraws its support to the government.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] On 14 July, the M5S eventually revoked the support to the government of national unity regarding a decree concerning economic stimulus to contrast the 2021 energy crisis.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] On the same day, Draghi resigned; his resignation was rejected by Mattarella.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] On 21 July, Draghi resigned again after a new confidence vote in the Senate failed to pass with an absolute majority, following defections of the M5S, the League, and FI.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] Mattarella accepted Draghi's resignation and asked him to remain in place to handle current affairs.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] On the following day, Mattarella officially dissolved the parliament and the snap election was called for 25 September 2022.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] Following the dissolution of Parliament, the electoral campaign officially began.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] Within the centre-left coalition, the Democratic Party (PD) secretary Enrico Letta ruled out an alliance with Giuseppe Conte's Five Star Movement (M5S), which he had always advocated in the previous months.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] Letta said that the government crisis brought an "irreversible break" between the two parties.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] Conte accused Letta of being "arrogant and hypocritical", and the League and Forza Italia (FI) of "having bullied" M5S "in front of the nation", adding that M5S would run alone in this election.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] Conte and M5S declared themselves to be part of the progressive pole and to the left of PD; their campaign centered around the minimum wage and in defense of the citizens' income against right-wing criticism.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] Letta criticised M5S for their past government with the League and anti-immigration measures.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] On 26 July, Italian Left (SI) and Green Europe (EV) officially launched their joint list for the upcoming election within the centre-left coalition, named Greens and Left Alliance (AVS).
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] After a few days, Angelo Bonelli was appointed political leader of the alliance on a eco-socialist platform.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] To their left, Power to the People (PaP), Communist Refoundation Party (PRC), and other minor left-wing and regionalist parties formed the People's Union (UP) coalition led by Luigi de Magistris, a former magistrate and mayor of Naples, on an anti-neoliberal platform.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] Gelmini and Carfagna were both ministers and long-time members of FI, who left Silvio Berlusconi's party after the fall of the Draghi government.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] They campaigned on the flat tax, constitutional reforms like presidentialism, welfare cuts, and citizen's income reform, though the three main parties and leaders had their differences, and their manifesto lacked details.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] Due to its strong showing in opinion polls, Giorgia Meloni's FdI gained 98 candidacies, Lega 70, FI–UdC 42, and NcI and CI 11.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] Meloni ran a campaign around the "God, country and family" slogan, downplayed FdI's post-fascist roots, and sought to promote her party as being mainstream conservative.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] On 29 July, the campaign was marked by the murder of Alika Ogorchukwu, a Nigerian migrant who was killed with bare hands and crutches by an Italian man in a street in Civitanova Marche.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] The murderer, a 32-year-old Italian, said that he acted because Ogorchukwu had been begging insistently.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] The murder was filmed by passers-by and made the front page of Italian newspapers on 29 July.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] The political class expressed its indignation following the murder, and the left and the right accused each other: the progressive parties and several commentators accused the right of spreading racist propaganda, while the right-wing parties accused the left of appropriating the murder.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] On 1 August, Luigi Di Maio and Bruno Tabacci presented their new party, Civic Commitment (IC), a centrist electoral list mainly composed by former members of M5S, which would be part of the centre-left coalition.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] Moreover, Marco Rizzo's Communist Party (PC), Antonio Ingroia's Civil Action (AC), and other minor populist and hard Eurosceptic parties launched Sovereign and Popular Italy (ISP), dubbed by the media as a red–brown alliance between left-wing and right-wing movements.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] On the same day, Gianluigi Paragone's Italexit and Pino Cabras's Alternative officially announced the formation of a Eurosceptic joint list, proposing the candidacies of several anti-vaccination and anti-lockdown activists.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] Four days later, Alternativa dissolved the alliance due to allegations about the presence of neofascist candidates within Italexit's lists, following an agreement between Paragone's party and CasaPound (CP).
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] On 2 August, Letta's PD signed an alliance with Calenda's Action party and Benedetto Della Vedova's More Europe (+E).
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] On 6 August, PD signed another pact with AVS and IC.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] These alliances caused tensions between Letta and Calenda.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] The latter, being a strong supporter of economic liberalism and nuclear power, considered impossible a coalition between his own party and AVS.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] On 7 August, Calenda broke the alliance with PD. +E, led by Della Vedova and Emma Bonino, decided to remain in the centre-left coalition with PD, marking the end of the federation between them and Calenda's party.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] On 11 August, Matteo Renzi's Italia Viva (IV) and A signed an agreement to create a centrist alliance led by Calenda, using IV's symbol to avoid collecting signatures for Calenda's party.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] Despite Draghi's dismissal, Calenda and Renzi said they would push for Draghi to remain as prime minister, should they win enough seats.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] They also ran a pro-nuclear power and pro-regasification campaign as solutions for the ongoing energy crisis.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] On 22 August, Meloni tweeted a video of a rape committed by a 27-year-old Guinean asylum seeker against a 55-year-old Ukrainian woman in the city of Piacenza, Emilia-Romagna.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] Letta immediately labeled Meloni as "indecent", adding that "the Italian right-wing has no respect for the victim, not caring about her rights", while Calenda stated that Meloni should be ashamed of herself.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] Meloni accused Letta of lying, saying that the video was taken from the official website of the newspaper *Il Messaggero*, adding that she did not have to apologize because it was done for solidarity with the victim.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] On 24 August, the rape victim stated that she was desperate for having been recognized by someone in the video of the attack.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] On the same day, the video was removed by Twitter, Facebook, and Instagram due to violations of the social media's policies.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] On the same day, a League councillor from Florence caused some controversy when he filmed a video saying that a vote for the League would be a vote to deport Roma people.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] On 9 September, Federico Mollicone, senior member of FdI, was criticised after he demanded for a *Peppa Pig* episode briefly showing a lesbian couple to be censored.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] On 20 September, FdI sacked Calogero Pisano, a member and candidate that openly praised Adolf Hitler; in an audio message, he expected to only be suspended for a few days.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] While he remained a candidate, FdI removed its symbol from his candidature.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] He was elected in the single-district constituency of Agrigento, Sicilia, with 37.8% of the vote.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] On 23 September, the centre-right coalition held a large rally in Rome, with closing statements and remarks from the main leaders of the alliance.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] On the same day, the other main coalitions and their leaders (PD, M5S, and A–IV) held their final rallies.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] According to Italian law, election silence was enforced over all the national territory on 24 September.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] Differently from many other Western countries, electoral debates between parties' leaders are not so common before general elections in Italy; the last debate between the two main candidates to prime ministry dated back to the 2006 Italian general election between Silvio Berlusconi and Romano Prodi.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] With few exceptions, almost every main political leader had denied his participation to an electoral debate with other candidates, preferring interviews with TV hosts and journalists, while many debates took place between other leading members of the main parties.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] The 2022 election saw the first debates between the main leaders in 16 years.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] On 23 August, some prominent leaders of the centre-right (Meloni, Salvini, Tajani, and Lupi) and of the centre-left (Letta and Di Maio) were jointly interviewed by Luciano Fontana during the Rimini Meeting, organized by the Catholic movement Communion and Liberation.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] Moreover, Fontana also interviewed the main parties' leaders at the Ambrosetti Forum on 4 September, and hosted a debate between Letta and Meloni on the website of *Corriere della Sera*, the newspaper of which he serves as director.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] By August 2022, the electoral reform was bogged down in the Chamber's Constitutional Affairs Commission and a proposal by M5S deputy Giuseppe Brescia had been presented to the Italian Parliament but by that time it was already dissolved for snap elections.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] Single-member district changes were approved and published on 30 December 2020 in *Gazzetta Ufficiale*, the Italian government gazette.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] The Chamber was reduced from 232 to 147 districts, and Senate districts were reduced from 116 to 74.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] For Italian residents, each house member is to be elected in single ballots, including the constituency candidate and their supporting party lists.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] In each single-member constituency, the deputy or senator is elected on a plurality basis, while the seats in multi-member constituencies are allocated nationally.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] In order to be calculated in single-member constituency results, parties need to obtain at least 1% of the national vote and be part of a coalition obtaining at least 10% of the national vote.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] In order to receive seats in multi-member constituencies, parties need to obtain at least 3% of the national vote.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] Elects from multi-member constituencies would come from closed lists.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] The voting paper, which is a single one for the FPTP and the proportional systems, shows the names of the candidates to single-member constituencies and in close conjunction with them the symbols of the linked lists for the proportional part, each one with a list of the relative candidates.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] Below are the main electoral lists that are running in the election.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] Since July 2022, when the snap election was first called, Brothers of Italy (FdI) was expected to become the first party, having surged as the opposition during the national unity government, and it became more likely as the election drew near.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] Early August polls showed the Action – Italia Viva (Third Pole) split from the centre-left coalition would not be influential in single-member districts but could cost votes for the centre-left in some competitive districts.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p01] Voter turnout was the lowest in the history of republican Italy at 63.9%, about 9 percentage points below the 2018 election.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] After the polls closed at 23:00 CEST, multiple Italian broadcasters published exit polls that projected the centre-right coalition would win a majority of seats in both the Chamber of Deputies and the Senate of the Republic.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] The vote count certified the victory of the centre-right coalition led by Brothers of Italy (FdI), which went from 4% in 2018 to 26%.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] The centre-right coalition won the absolute majority of seats in both houses of Parliament, with 237 seats in the Chamber and 115 in the Senate.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] First within the alliance came FdI (26.0%), followed by the League (8.7%) and Forza Italia (8.1%), both of whom suffered losses.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] Us Moderates failed to reach the 1% threshold and have their votes for the centre-right coalition in the national proportional representation but won 7 seats in the Chamber and 2 seats in the Senate thanks to the first-past-the-post (FPTP) system.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] The centre-left coalition slightly improved its 2018 popular vote result but came a distant second in terms of seats, 85 in the Chamber and 44 in the Senate, winning only a few more FPTP seats than the Five Star Movement (M5S).
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] The M5S saw its vote more than halved and won 52 seats in the Chamber and 28 in the Senate but defied single-digits polls in July 2022 by winning 15.4% of the popular vote, thanks in part to a strong performance in Southern Italy.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] Due to FPTP seats, the League was able to gain more seats in both chambers than the M5S and barely less than the PD (69 to 66 in the Chamber and 40 to 30 in the Senate), despite polling half than the PD and about a third of the M5S in the popular vote.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] The centrist list composed of Action and Italia Viva (Third Pole) won 21 seats in the Chamber and 9 in the Senate, with 7.8% of the vote.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] Using the Gallagher index, the disproportionality of the Chamber in the election was 12.31 and 10.83 for the Senate; for comparison, the disproportionality in the 2018 election for both houses was 5.50 and 6.12.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] According to political analyst Wolfango Piccoli, an estimated 30% of voters chose a different party than the one they had voted for in 2018.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] In Sicily, the party South calls North won 1 seat in the Chamber and 1 in the Senate.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] Linguistic minorities representatives like Aosta Valley and the South Tyrolean People's Party also won seats, as well as the Italians-abroad party Associative Movement of Italians Abroad.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] The autonomous region of Aosta Valley in northwestern Italy elects one member to the Chamber of Deputies through a direct first-past-the-post election.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] Some parties that formed electoral coalitions in Italy might have opted to run against one another, or form different coalitions, in this particular region.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] Eight members of the Chamber of Deputies are elected by Italians abroad.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] Two members are elected for North America and Central America (including most of the Caribbean), two members for South America (including Trinidad and Tobago), three members for Europe, and one member for the rest of the world (Africa, Asia, Oceania, and Antarctica).
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] Voters in these regions select candidate lists and cast a preference vote for individual candidates.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] The seats are allocated by proportional representation.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] The electoral law allows for parties to form different coalitions on the lists abroad, compared to the lists in Italy; Forza Italia, the League, and Brothers of Italy formed a unified list for abroad constituencies.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] Four members of the Senate of the Republic are elected by Italians abroad.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] One member is elected for North America and Central America (including most of the Caribbean), one member for South America (including Trinidad and Tobago), one member for Europe, and one for the rest of the world (Africa, Asia, Oceania, and Antarctica).
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] The electoral law allows for parties to form different coalitions on the lists abroad, compared to the lists in Italy; since January 2018, Forza Italia, the League, and Brothers of Italy have formed a unified list for abroad constituencies.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] Of party leaders, Meloni (FdI), Berlusconi (FI), Bonelli (AVS), and Lupi (NM) won in their respective first-past-the-post (FPTP) seats.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] Others like Di Maio (IC), Bonino (+E), and Calenda (A–IV) lost their FPTP election; Calenda won a seat in the proportional representation (PR) lists.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] Letta (PD), Conte (M5S), and Salvini (Lega) did not run in FPTP elections, and won their seats in the PR apportionment.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] In a record-low voter turnout election, exit polls projected that the centre-right coalition would win a majority of seats.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] Giorgia Meloni was projected to be the winner of the election.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] She would be Italy's first female Prime Minister, the first far-right head of government of a major eurozone country, and its first far-right leader since Benito Mussolini, and lead the most right-wing government since World War II.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] According to observers, the result of the Italian election, together with far-right gains in the 2022 Spanish regional elections in February and June, the 2022 French legislative election in April, and the 2022 Swedish general election earlier on 11 September shifted the geopolitics of Europe.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] Historian Timothy Garton Ash argued that "Meloni is undoubtedly an anti-immigration, rightwing populist, a strong social conservative and a Eurosceptic nationalist ...
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] The centre-right coalition successfully took advantage of the majoritarian system and stayed united, which the left and centre were not able to achieve.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] The Five Star Movement (M5S) finished third in terms of popular vote, avoiding an even bigger victory for the right.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] Despite the win of the right-wing alliance, both Forza Italia and the League suffered losses.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] Leila Simona Talani of King's College London said that a right-wing government would face many issues and questioned their economic experience.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] Political scientist Lorenzo Castellani commented that the stability and durability of a right-wing government depended on the final results.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] He said that, at 44%, the Meloni-led coalition "can govern in a much more stable way, without problems".
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] At 42%, they would have had a smaller majority, while a 46–47% result could have given them the necessary first-past-the-post seats to reach the two-thirds supermajority and approve constitutional reforms without a referendum.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] Observers, such as political scientist Giovanni Orsina, said that far-right supporters would be disappointed by a Meloni government because she is now part of the mainstream right like the Conservative Party in the United Kingdom.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] The Democratic Party (PD), the head of the centre-left coalition, conceded defeat shortly after the exit polls.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] Other European radical right parties and leaders, such as Alternative for Germany and Vox in Spain, also celebrated the right-wing victory.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] Enrico Letta, the PD's secretary, stated "the trend that emerged two weeks ago in Sweden was confirmed in Italy", described it as a "sad day for Italy, for Europe", and called for a reflection within the party.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] Letta added that his party would provide a "strong and intransigent opposition", and announced he would not stand for the 2023 PD leadership election.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] European Union (EU) officials were reportedly anxious about the aftermath of the results, with France's prime minister Élisabeth Borne saying the EU would follow the situation to make sure that human rights and EU values, including women's access to abortion, are respected.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] The European Commission expressed their hope towards a positive relationship with the next Italian government.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] France's president Emmanuel Macron said his country respected the electoral results and that "as neighbors and friends, we must continue to work together.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] It is within Europe that we will overcome our common challenges." In the United States, the Biden administration was reportedly worried by the results but pledged for cooperation, while prominent Republican Party members celebrated FdI's results.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] About a Meloni-led government, Stefano Stefanini, Italy's former ambassador to NATO, stated: "The faithful need to know that her government would be tough on immigration, critical of the EU, and based on traditional values.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] Moderates, markets and the foreign allies want continuity." Ukraine's president Volodymyr Zelenskyy congratulated Meloni on her victory and expressed interest in collaborating with her government, especially in regard to the Russian invasion of Ukraine.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] The Russian government was reported to be pleased by the results.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] Several politicians also congratulated Meloni, especially centre-right and right-wing politicians worldwide, including in Australia, France, Germany, Hungary, Poland and Spain.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] French newspaper *Libération* portrayed the election result as "post-fascism in power", as well as a "European earthquake". while the German *Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung* commented that "Meloni is not the devil", and that "the economy hopes for stability".
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] *Die Zeit* observed that whether Meloni would form a new government depends on President Mattarella.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] The newly elected legislature was seated on 13 October.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] That same day, Ignazio La Russa of Brothers of Italy was elected President of the Senate of the Republic.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] He is the first politician with a neo-fascist background and to come from a post-fascist party to hold the position, which is the second highest-ranking office of the Italian Republic.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] He was elected with some votes from parties outside the centre-right coalition, as Forza Italia did not vote.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] La Russa was proclaimed president by Liliana Segre, a senator for life and Holocaust survivor, who presided the Senate's session due to her being the oldest senator.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] On 14 October, the League's Lorenzo Fontana, who is widely seen as an ultraconservative for his long-time anti-abortion and anti-LGBT views, was elected President of the Chamber of Deputies.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] As per constitutional convention, the new government formation are preceded by rounds of talks between party leaders and President of Italy, Sergio Mattarella, which took place on 20–21 October.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] On 21 October, Mattarella gave Meloni the task of forming a new government, which was officially sworn in on the following day.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] The talks were marred by controversy within the centre-right coalition, in particular between Silvio Berlusconi and Meloni, whom Berlusconi described as "patronising, overbearing, arrogant" and "offensive" in a series of written notes in the Senate.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2022-italian-general-election-p02] Additionally, Berlusconi's views of the Russian invasion of Ukraine and Vladimir Putin, with whom he said he was rekindling their friendship and claimed to have received vodka as gift and exchanged letters, during a group session with his own party were leaked through an audio.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] The **2024 European Parliament election in Italy** took place on 8 and 9 June 2024, electing members of the 10th Italian delegation to the European Parliament as part of the broader 2024 European Parliament election from 6 to 9 June.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] It was held concurrently with the 2024 Italian local elections.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] In the 2019 European Parliament election in Italy, the right-wing populist League (Lega) of Matteo Salvini arrived first with 34.3% of the vote and 29 seats, followed by the centre-left Democratic Party (PD) with 22.7% and 19 seats.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] In the 2022 Italian general election, the national-conservative Brothers of Italy (FdI) of Giorgia Meloni arrived first with 25.9% of the vote for the Chamber of Deputies, inside the centre-right coalition, followed by the PD with 19.0%, inside the centre-left coalition.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] This resulted in the establishment of the Meloni government, which was widely described as the most right-wing since World War II and continued to lead in the opinion polling for the next Italian general election.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] The ongoing Qatargate corruption scandal, which began in December 2022, destabilised the European Parliament following the arrest of several MEPs including Marc Tarabella, Andrea Cozzolino, and Eva Kaili.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] Calovini was then elected member of the Chamber of Deputies of Italy at the 2022 general election for FdI.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] In June 2023, Fidanza and Calovini plea bargained with the Milan Public Prosecutor to one year and four months for corruption, avoiding the disqualification from public office that would have been triggered by the Severino Law.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] As the party-list proportional representation was the traditional electoral system of the First Italian Republic from its establishment in 1946 to 1994, it was adopted to elect the Italian members of the European Parliament (MEPs) since 1979.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] Two levels were introduced: a national level to divide the seats among parties and a constituency level to distribute them among candidates in open lists.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] Five constituencies were established, each including 2–6 Italian regions and each electing a fixed number of MEPs.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] At national level, seats are divided between party lists using the largest remainder method with Hare quota.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] Seats are allocated to parties and then to their most voted candidates.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] In the run-up to the 2009 European Parliament election in Italy, the Italian Parliament introduced a national electoral threshold of 4%.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] The latter condition was established in 2019 by the Electoral Offices of the constituencies.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] In 2023, the Regional Council of Sardinia unanimously approved a proposal to split the Italian Islands constituency into Sicily and Sardinia due to the population disproportion between the two Italian regions.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] As of May 2023, the proposal is under discussion in the Senate of the Republic.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] In July 2023, it was informally proposed to lower the electoral threshold from 4% to 3%, the same electoral threshold used for the political elections.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] This proposal was welcomed by Greens and Left Alliance (AVS) and Us Moderates (NM).
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] FdI did not shut it down since they wanted to help FI, whose future seemed uncertain after the death of Berlusconi, while Lega and IV declared themselves against the proposal.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] The proposal was officially rejected in September when Forza Italia, fearing the centrist competition of Az and IV, refused to lower the electoral threshold.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] In 2014, the Electoral Offices of the constituencies granted exemption to the European Greens – Green Italia list, as the list was affiliated with a European political party represented in the European Parliament with its own parliamentary group.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] In 2019, the Electoral Offices of the constituencies established a condition that permits certain parties to participate in European elections through any party in Europe that elected at least one MEP in any European country.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] In February 2024, FdI proposed an amendment to the Elections Decree in the Senate of the Republic.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] The amendment aimed to clarify the interpretation given by the Electoral Offices of the constituencies in 2019.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] It was suggested that parties that had elected at least one MEP in Italy at the last elections would be exempt.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] Additionally, it was proposed that only lists that had elected at least one member of the Italian Parliament (MP) in the proportional representation system (Italian electoral law of 2017) at the 2022 general election would be exempt.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] This exclusion would apply to parties that had elected an MP in a single-member constituency (Italian: *collegio uninominale*) with their party logo.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] On 7 March 2024, the Constitutional Affairs Committee in the Senate of the Republic approved the amendment.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] The table shows the detailed composition of the Italian seats at the European Parliament as of 1 February 2024.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] Raffaele Stancanelli, an outgoing MEP of Brothers of Italy, was a candidate for the League.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] Maria Veronica Rossi left the League and joined Brothers of Italy on 30 April 2024.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] Andrea Cozzolino was suspended from the Democratic Party on 16 December 2022 following the Qatar corruption scandal at the European Parliament.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] The table shows the MEPs who did not seek re-election.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] This is a list of the parties that took part to the election.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] Some parties ran only in one or a few constituencies out of five.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] The following table lists the top candidates of each party/list in the five constituencies.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] On 8 January 2024, Salvini announced that he would not run for the next European Parliament.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] He also praised Roberto Vannacci, an Italian Army general who became notorious in the summer of 2023 for writing a political book containing statements considered homophobic, racist, and sexist by some while on duty.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] An internal disciplinary procedure was opened against him by the Italian Army to investigate possible disciplinary offences.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] Vannacci said he would consider a candidature for the European elections.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] On 25 April, Salvini announced that Vannacci accepted to run as a candidate in all constituencies.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] Paolo Gentiloni, the outgoing European Commissioner for Economy, turned down the chance to stand as a candidate for the European Parliament.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] Meloni, the leader of FdI and 68th Prime Minister of Italy, said during a press conference that she was considering running in the election.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] According to Article 122 of the Italian Constitution and to Article 6 of the Access Initial Legal Act approved by the European Parliament, the office of Prime Minister is incompatible with that of MEP, therefore Meloni should immediately resign as MEP.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] Berlusconi was the only italian incumbent Prime Minister to run as a candidate for the European elections in 1994, 2004, and 2009, resigning as MEP after the elections due to incompatibility with the office of Prime Minister.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] On 14 January 2024, Emma Bonino declined to stand as a candidate for the election; she changed her mind on 20 April 2024.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] On 25 January 2024, Federico Pizzarotti, president of +Eu, announced his desire to run as a candidate.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] On 22 January 2024, Calenda unveiled on the party website the first candidates for the election: MEP Giosi Ferrandino, Caterina Avanza, Alessio D'Amato, Cristina Lodi, Mario Raffaelli, and Giuseppe Zollino.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] In an interview with ZDF on 6 August 2023, the EPP president Manfred Weber praised the Meloni government, suggesting a possible alliance with FdI for the next election.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] Former German Minister of Justice Katarina Barley accused Weber of opening up to the far right in Europe.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] During the press conference held on 5 January 2024, Meloni said there are "insurmountable distances" with AfD but praised Le Pen.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] Stéphane Séjourné, the president of Renew, publicly appealed in May 2023 to both parties to stand together at the next European elections so as to elect "as many MEPs from the Renew Europe group as possible".
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] Disagreements between Az leader Carlo Calenda and IV leader Matteo Renzi hindered the birth of a common list; Renzi announced the break-up of the common groups at the Italian Parliament and the birth of a list called The Centre, while Calenda expressed his opposition to run again with Renzi.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] On 30 September 2023, Riccardo Magi, the secretary of +Eu, announced that his party would run as United States of Europe.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] On 13 December 2023, the National Direction of +Eu approved talks with the other Italian liberal parties for a list supporting a federal Europe.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] On 15 December 2023, Bonino published on *La Stampa* a manifesto, calling for the United States of Europe.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] The manifesto was signed by individual people like Base Italia leader Marco Bentivogli, Giusi Nicolini, Sandro Gozi, Nathalie Tocci, and Renato Soru, and parties like IV.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] On 31 January 2024, Bonino published an article in *Il Sole 24 Ore* announcing a convention for the United States of Europe list open to all parties for 24 February 2024 in Rome.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] The goal was to launch a list that did not contain individual party symbols on its logo and that party leaders would not run for the European Parliament election.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] Despite supporting the manifesto, Renzi announced that he would run in all constituencies.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] Following the convention on 24 February 2024, there were differences of opinion between Az and IV.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] Magi requested a brief period of reflection to come to an agreement on a single list.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] On 7 March 2024, +Eu issued a statement advocating for a unified list that includes all three liberal parties, otherwise each party would need to act independently.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] In November 2023, former Rome mayor Gianni Alemanno launched a right-wing party called Independence, saying he was thinking about running for the European Parliament election.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] In February 2024, television host Michele Santoro presented a left-wing list named Peace, Land, Dignity.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] In what was the European Parliament election in Italian history with the lowest voter turnout (48.3% compared to the 54.5% of 2019), FdI emerged as the largest party with almost 29% of the votes.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] The results were thus seen as a victory for the incumbent Meloni government; however, the combined number of seats obtained by the most Eurosceptic and anti-European Green Deal government parties (FdI and Lega) was three seats lower than in 2019.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] The liberal and centrist parties and electoral lists narrowly failed to reach the 4% threshold.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] As the parties suffering the most losses in terms of seats and votes, the League and M5S were seen as the biggest losers compared to the 2019.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] Compared to the 2022 general election results, even as they increased or held similar percentage points, all the government parties lost total votes.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] The only parties that gained more votes compared to 2022 were the PD and AVS, which together surpassed FdI.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/2024-european-parliament-election-in-italy] The youth vote among those under 30 in Italy favoured the Progressive Camp of the PD, M5S, and AVS at 51%.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe] The **Alliance for Direct Democracy in Europe**, abbreviated to **ADDE**, was a European political party founded in 2014.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe] It was composed of parties belonging to the Europe of Freedom and Direct Democracy (EFDD) group in the European Parliament (EP).
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe] The dominant national party in the ADDE was the UK Independence Party (UKIP), providing 21 of the party's 27 members of the European Parliament (MEPs) elected in 2014.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe] A further three UKIP MEPs chose not to participate in the ADDE.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe] In 2015, the ADDE was recognised by the European Parliament and its grant maximum from the EP was set at €1,241,725, with an additional €730,053 for its affiliated political foundation, the *Initiative for Direct Democracy*.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe] ADDE was closed down in 2016 after an auditors' inquiry found misspending of EU funds.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe] The party was legally dissolved on 24 May 2017.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-for-europe-of-the-nations] The **Alliance for Europe of the Nations** was a European political party that gathered conservative and national-conservative political parties from across the continent.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-for-europe-of-the-nations] The AEN was founded in 2002, designed to complement the existing Union for Europe of the Nations group in the European Parliament.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-for-europe-of-the-nations] Moves towards establishing standardised funding block grants for European political parties were at this point well afoot, and the parties affiliated with UEN required a corresponding organisation to take advantage of them.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-for-europe-of-the-nations] Almost immediately upon its founding, the AEN began to decline in terms of membership and influence.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-for-europe-of-the-nations] At its first meeting, participants included the Czech Civic Democratic Party, Portuguese CDS-PP, Israeli Likud, Irish Fianna Fáil, Italian National Alliance and the Greek Popular Orthodox Rally, all of which later left the organisation.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-for-europe-of-the-nations] The AEN had a broadly national-conservative political line, but many members were uncomfortable with this.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-for-europe-of-the-nations] There was a strong movement for the centrist Fianna Fáil to leave AEN and join the European Liberal Democrat and Reform Party, which it did on 17 April 2009.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-for-europe-of-the-nations] After those realignments, there were too few AEN member parties left to retain its EU-funded status as a European political party.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The **Alliance for Peace and Freedom** (**APF**) is a far-right European political alliance and former European political party founded on 4 February 2015.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The main member parties were involved in the defunct **European National Front**.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The alliance wishes to establish a network of nationalist movements across Europe that will cooperate to strengthen their shared ideals.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] It cooperates and supports other nationalist groups across Europe that are not members, these include former party members Golden Dawn, Tricolour Flame, Alternative for Sweden and the ELAM.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The alliance is described as neo-Nazi by several newspapers, and neo-fascist by others.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The group works for "a Europe of sovereign nations in which the independent states work together on a confederated basis", and for the perennity and the safeguarding of ancestral European traditions such as the Christian tradition.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The Europa Terra Nostra is the official European political foundation of the APF.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The ETN was founded 3 July 2015 in Berlin where it continues to operate as the official think-tank of the APF and serves as the European framework for national foundations/think-tanks recognised by APF member-parties.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The APF works to co-ordinate European nationalist parties across the continent.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] It helped establish the Italy for the Italians coalition composed of APF member New Force along with Tricolour Flame.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] In 2017 the APF aided in the formation of the National Identity Bloc in Europe coalition, APF members, United Romania Party and Noua Dreaptă joined forces with the Greater Romania Party.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] In 2019 The APF played a part in forming the ADÑ Identidad Española coalition, composed of APF member National Democracy, FE-JONS, Spanish Alternative and La Falange.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The party also maintains contacts with the former leader of the National Front, Jean-Marie Le Pen, who was expelled from his party in 2015.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] He joined the group in March 2018 as an Honorary Chairman and held this position until his death in January 2025.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The APF maintains contacts with conservative circles in Russia with the group being invited to conferences hosted by the Kremlin.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The party supports Vladimir Putin and United Russia's leadership of Russia, especially in the Russo-Ukrainian War and Syrian Civil War.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The party is supportive of Alexander Lukashenko and maintains contacts with the Liberal Democratic Party of Belarus.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The APF strongly supports Serbian nationalists and is opposed to international recognition of Kosovo, it has worked in the past with the Serbian Radical Party.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] On 26 September 2021, the APF held a conference in Belgrade hosted by the Serbian Right.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] It maintained friendly relations with the Syrian Arab Socialist Ba'ath Party government with deputy chairman, Nick Griffin being invited to Syria by Bashar al-Assad multiple times as an ambassador.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] Meetings between the party and the Syrian Social Nationalist Party have been held with the AFP publicly supporting the SSNP.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The group maintains contacts with Hezbollah and has hosted at least one meeting with Hezbollah leaders.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] Michel Aoun, then president of Lebanon, received a delegation of the APF in 2018 and in 2019, and the group claims to have been in regular contact with him and his party.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-of-european-national-movements] The **Alliance of European National Movements** (**AENM**) was a European political party that was formed in Budapest on 24 October 2009 by a number of ultranationalist and far-right parties from countries in Europe.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-of-european-national-movements] AENM's founding members were Jobbik (the alliance was established during their sixth party congress), France's National Front, Italy's Tricolour Flame, Sweden's National Democrats and Belgium's National Front.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-of-european-national-movements] At the end of 2011, the National Front withdrew from AENM and joined the European Alliance for Freedom (EAF).
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-of-european-national-movements] In 2014, the All-Ukrainian Union "Freedom" terminated its observer status in the AENM, due to many members of the bloc showing support for Russia in the Russo-Ukrainian war.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-of-european-national-movements] In February 2016, Jobbik cut all of its affiliation with AENM, and the president of AENM Béla Kovács left Jobbik.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-of-european-national-movements] In November 2009, the British National Party claimed that AENM had been extended to nine parties, but this information was not confirmed by AENM President Bruno Gollnisch in 2012.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-of-european-national-movements] At a press conference held in Strasbourg on 16 June 2010, the political leadership of AENM was confirmed as follows: President Bruno Gollnisch, Vice President Nick Griffin, Treasurer Béla Kovács and Secretary General Valerio Cignetti.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-of-european-national-movements] At the end of 2011 the National Front withdrew from AENM and joined the European Alliance for Freedom.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-of-european-national-movements] However, Gollnisch and Jean-Marie Le Pen maintained their position in the organisation.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-of-european-national-movements] In October 2013, Marine Le Pen requested that Gollnisch and Jean-Marie Le Pen leave their positions in the AENM in order to join the more moderate EAF and so unify the French National Front under the EAF banner.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-of-european-national-movements] Marine Le Pen has tried to "de-demonize" the party, i.e. to give it a more acceptable image.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-of-european-national-movements] Cooperation with the openly racist and antisemitic parties present in AENM was seen as contradictory to these aims.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-of-european-national-movements] On November 7, the two declared they have followed the request and left AENM.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-of-european-national-movements] This also meant the end of Gollnisch's term as the AENM's chairman, a place occupied by Béla Kovács since January 2014.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-of-european-national-movements] In the spring of 2013, Svoboda lost its observer status after a conflict with other member groups over its policies towards ethnic minorities in the West of Ukraine.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-of-european-national-movements] Béla Kovács, leader of the alliance, had served as an observer at the 2014 Donbass parliamentary election.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-of-european-national-movements] In 2014, there were accusations against Chairman Kovács that he or his wife were working for the Russian intelligence service.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-of-european-national-movements] In 2015 the European Parliament lifted Kovács immunity.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-of-european-national-movements] In September 2020, he was cleared of the charge of espionage.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-of-european-national-movements] However, he had worked with the Russian secret service SVR RF, but mostly in the form of influencing, with the aim to promote Russian interests through the AEMN.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-of-european-national-movements] Kovács was sentenced to one and a half years imprisonment for fraud and falsification of documents to the detriment of the European Parliament.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-of-european-national-movements] The party did not apply for registration with the newly established Authority for European Political Parties and European Political Foundations (APPF), which was required from 2017, in good time.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-of-european-national-movements] An application by the party foundation ITE was rejected by the APPF, as the AEMN was not registered itself at that time.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-of-european-national-movements] Subsequently, the AEMN's application for funding for 2018 was rejected accordingly.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-of-european-national-movements] Finally, the AEMN was registered as a European political party on 12 January 2018.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-of-european-national-movements] At the end of 2018, the AENM was removed from the register again.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-of-european-national-movements] The background was a change in the registration rules, according to which European parties had to submit member parties (with parliamentarians) from seven EU member states in the register.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-of-european-national-movements] This put an end to the previous practice of AENM registering individual parliamentarians from national parties who did not belong to AENM but to other European parties.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-of-european-national-movements] For example, parliamentarians from the Front National had regularly provided signatures for the AENM, the APF and the MENL – to which the FN belongs.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-of-european-national-movements] For the 2019 European Parliament election, AEMN chairman Kovacs provided the necessary signature of support for the candidacy of the Italian party CasaPound Italia.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-of-european-national-movements] None of the parties in the AEMN's environment was able to win mandates in the election.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-of-european-national-movements] After the election, the party was no longer active.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-of-european-national-movements] For the 2024 European Parliament election in Italy, Royal Italy submitted a symbol with the text "Alleanza europea dei movimenti nazionali" at the top.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-of-european-national-movements] In 2022, Royal Italy ran with United Right who made a deal with CasaPound in 2019.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe] The **Alliance of Independent Democrats in Europe** (AIDE) (**Alliance des Démocrates Indépendants en Europe** (ADIE) in French) was a Eurosceptic, nationalist European political party.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe] AIDE was created on 28 October 2005 in the Rhône prefecture.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe] AIDE described itself as the centre-right faction of the eurosceptic IND/DEM group, with the EUDemocrats, the United Kingdom Independence Party and the European Christian Political Movement comprising the other factions of that group.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe] As of January 2007, the group operated a limited French-language website.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe] The group's website implied the existence of British, Czech, French, Greek, Irish, Italian and Polish delegations and identified Movement for France (MpF) MEP Patrick Louis as the president of AIDE.
[src:alliance-of-european-national-movements/alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe] AIDE was dissolved with effect from 31 December 2008 and was defunded in the February 2009 meeting of the Bureau of the European Parliament.
